h3. Issue Summary

Plans can be stuck in a {{*RUNNING*}} state and do not progress.
h3. Environment
 * Confluence 5.10. or above
 * Latest CMAC

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a Plan for a large Space
 # Start the Plan
 # Kill Confluence with {{kill -9}} (do not do this in production)
 # Restart Confluence

h3. Expected Results

Plans should re-start
h3. Actual Results

Plans say {{*RUNNING*}}, however there is no progression of the Plan and it stays in the same state.
h3. Notes

This is caused by the running thread being killed and CMAC not cleaning up invalid Plans on restart.
h3. Workaround
(i) See also the [Restore the Cloud Migration Assistant for Confluence to the default version|https://confluence.atlassian.com/confkb/restore-the-cloud-migration-assistant-for-confluence-to-the-default-version-974378747.html] guide.

{panel:title=IMPORTANT|borderStyle=dashed|borderColor=#cccccc|titleBGColor=#f7d6c1|bgColor=#ffffce}
(!) Always back up your data before performing any modifications to the database. If possible, test any alter, insert, update, or delete SQL commands on a staging server first.
{panel}
 # Stop Confluence
 # Remove CMAC completely (this will remove all the current Plans and associated data)
{code:sql|title=For PostgreSQL}
DELETE FROM public.plugindata WHERE plugindata.pluginkey = 'com.atlassian.migration.agent';
DROP TABLE "public"."mig_analytics_event" CASCADE;
DROP TABLE "public"."mig_attachment" CASCADE;
DROP TABLE "public"."mig_cloud_site" CASCADE;
DROP TABLE "public"."mig_db_changelog" CASCADE;
DROP TABLE "public"."mig_db_changelog_lock" CASCADE;
DROP TABLE "public"."mig_plan" CASCADE;
DROP TABLE "public"."mig_sequences" CASCADE;
DROP TABLE "public"."mig_stats" CASCADE;
DROP TABLE "public"."mig_step" CASCADE;
DROP TABLE "public"."mig_task" CASCADE;
DROP TABLE "public"."mig_work_item" CASCADE;
{code}

 # Restart Confluence

h3. Issue Summary
When upgrading CMAC from 1.0.9 (the embedded version) to latest, if a plan is running while the upgrade happens then the threads are shutdown without the plans finishing. ON restart, the data is inconsistent.

h3. Environment
 * A version of Confluence with CMAC 1.0.9

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Start a fresh Confluence with CMAC 1.0.9
 # Create some spaces and start the migration plan
 # Upgrade CMAC before the plans have finished

h3. Expected Results
CMAC should handle the old data correctly in the database tables.

h3. Actual Results
The below exception (for example) is thrown in the {{atlassian-confluence.log}} file:
{noformat}
2019-05-31 11:04:57,463 ERROR [Caesium-1-3] [migration.agent.queue.QueueBroker] error An error occurred when getting the next batch for consumer type: ATTACHMENT_UPLOAD. Message: No enum constant com.atlassian.migration.agent.entity.WorkItem.Status.STOPPED
java.lang.IllegalArgumentException: No enum constant com.atlassian.migration.agent.entity.WorkItem.Status.STOPPED
{noformat}
h3. Notes

h3. Workaround

(i) See also the [Restore the Cloud Migration Assistant for Confluence to the default version|https://confluence.atlassian.com/confkb/restore-the-cloud-migration-assistant-for-confluence-to-the-default-version-974378747.html] guide.

 # Drop CMAC and the migration tables from the database (some tables might not exist or have different foreign key relationships. Run this again if there are foreign key contsraints.) (This is for MySQL, adjust as necessary)
{code:java}
delete from confluence.PLUGINDATA where PLUGINDATA.PLUGINKEY = 'com.atlassian.migration.agent';
DROP TABLE `confluence`.`MIG_ANALYTICS_EVENT`;
DROP TABLE `confluence`.`MIG_ATTACHMENT`;
DROP TABLE `confluence`.`MIG_DB_CHANGELOG_LOCK`;
DROP TABLE `confluence`.`MIG_DB_CHANGELOG`;
DROP TABLE `confluence`.`MIG_SEQUENCES`;
DROP TABLE `confluence`.`MIG_STATS`;
DROP TABLE `confluence`.`MIG_STEP`;
DROP TABLE `confluence`.`MIG_TASK`;
DROP TABLE `confluence`.`MIG_WORK_ITEM`;
DROP TABLE `confluence`.`MIG_PLAN`;
DROP TABLE `confluence`.`MIG_CLOUD_SITE`;
{code}
Reinstall CMAC from Marketplace and recreate the plans.

This is similar to plans being stuck in RUNNING state when Confluence restarts.
